        "last_activity_date": 1299262769,
        "creation_date": 1299259480,
        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "PHP - Using Exec to execute Jar file with user defined parameters",
        "body": "<p>I have a working exec in php that executes a Jar file and returns back result:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>exec('java -jar Clt.jar ' . $sampleSize . ' ' . $numberOfSamples . ' ' . $randAlgorithm,  $output);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>These parameters are checked in Java application in the following way:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>int sampleSize = Integer.parseInt(args[0]);\nint numberOfSamples = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);\nint randGenerator = Integer.parseInt(args[2]);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now I need to know If I need to check user input, because on PHP page under exec, it says:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>When allowing user-supplied data to be passed to this function, use escapeshellarg() or escapeshellcmd() to ensure that users cannot trick the system into executing arbitrary commands.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>But in my case, where user input is used only as parameter for application, are there any security risks If I do not check what has user set, apart from that program will not execute if user enters string or floating point number?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 5197104,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "php",
            "security",
            "exec"
        ],
        "score": 2,
        "accepted_answer_id": 5197133,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 2426
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7cedb843eb2922000eb41b4561ed660d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 61611,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 183528,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/183528/rook",
                "reputation": 67129,
                "display_name": "rook",
                "accept_rate": 95
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1299262769,
            "creation_date": 1299259684,
            "body": "<p><code>But in my case, where user input is used only as parameter for application<\/code> <\/p>\n\n<p>And this is where you are wrong.  <code>exec()<\/code> is as if you are executing a line on the command-line.   What if the users inputs something like: <code>; rm -rf / &amp;&amp; echo<\/code>.  You must escape the input with <code>escapeshellargs()<\/code>.  Or even better use <code>floatval()<\/code> before passing it to the commandline.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 5197133,
            "question_id": 5197104,
            "last_edit_date": 1299262769
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/pIZKW.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 153959,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 369591,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/369591/brandon-frohbieter",
                "reputation": 18247,
                "display_name": "Brandon Frohbieter",
                "accept_rate": 88
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299259759,
            "creation_date": 1299259759,
            "body": "<p>Absolutely. There are plenty of shell hacks that will allow the user to escape your command and execute arbitrary commands on your system. Using &amp;&amp;, piping, etc...<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 5197143,
            "question_id": 5197104
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/37458c7c44851cd6c402e02e5a9be94f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 46833,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 138475,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/138475/pascal-martin",
                "reputation": 401928,
                "display_name": "Pascal MARTIN"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299259796,
            "creation_date": 1299259796,
            "body": "<p>If you do not check nor escape what you inject into that command-line you're executing, it means anyone can inject anything into it. Which means getting any kind of code executing on your system. And, as you'll probably guess, this can be <strong>bad<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>You must <strong>always<\/strong> properly escape <em>(especially)<\/em> unsafe data !<\/p>\n<br>\nWhen building commands that are to be executed by the system, you should use the [**`escapeshellarg()`**][1] function.\n",
            "answer_id": 5197153,
            "question_id": 5197104,
            "last_edit_date": 1700250178
        }
    ],
